## Useful One-Liners

```bash
# Check if the gateway is up
curl -s http://127.0.0.1:8000/health/ready | jq

# List Ollama models
curl -s http://127.0.0.1:11434/api/tags | jq '.models[].name'

# Query memory.db for recent documents
sqlite3 ~/.synapse/workspace/db/memory.db "SELECT id, category, substr(content,1,80) FROM documents ORDER BY id DESC LIMIT 5"

# Query knowledge graph for a name
sqlite3 ~/.synapse/workspace/db/knowledge_graph.db "SELECT * FROM nodes WHERE name LIKE '%Shreya%' LIMIT 10"

# Hot-reload config after editing synapse.json
curl -s -X POST http://127.0.0.1:8000/reload_config -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{}'

# Ingest a quick memory
curl -s -X POST http://127.0.0.1:8000/add -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"content":"Upayan prefers Python for scripting","category":"tech_preferences"}'
```

## Why Separate from Skills?

Skills are shared / portable — they teach *concepts* (how to swap a model, how to query memory). This file is *your* environment — what's actually installed on this machine, the nicknames Upayan uses, which hosts are reachable. Keeping them apart means you can update skills without losing your notes, and share skills without leaking your infrastructure.

